<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910918-0038</DOCNO><DOCID>910918-0038.</DOCID><HL>   Texas Charges Makers   Of Infant Formula   In Antitrust Lawsuit</HL><DATE>09/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   ABT BMY</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)MEDICAL SUPPLIES, EYEGLASS MANUFACTURERS (MDS)</IN><NS>ANTITRUST NEWS (TST)</NS><RE>ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   AUSTIN -- The Texas attorney general sued two makers ofinfant formula and a national pediatricians' association,charging that they violated state antitrust laws by trying tofix prices, restrain competition and rig government bids.   In a suit filed in state court here, Attorney General DanMorales charged that Abbott Laboratories, Bristol-MyersSquibb Co. and the American Academy of Pediatrics helped todrive up the price of hundreds of thousands of units ofinfant formula sold to the federal government and distributedby the Texas Department of Health.</LP><TEXT>   The companies, and others who make infant formula, weresued earlier this year by law enforcement authorities inFlorida, charging violations of state antitrust laws. Inaddition, the Federal Trade Commission said earlier this yearthat it is investigating alleged price-fixing by infantformula manufacturers.   The companies involved and the American Academy ofPediatrics, have denied any wrongdoing in conjunction withthe federal investigation.</TEXT></DOC>